TY  - JOUR
T1  - Strategic Alliance Structuring: A Game Theoretic and Transaction Cost Examination of Interfirm Cooperation
AU  - Parkhe, Arvind
Y1  - 1993/08/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256759
DO  - 10.5465/256759
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 794
EP  - 829
VL  - 36
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Maintaining robust cooperation in interfirm strategic alliances poses special problems. Such relationships have received growing attention in recent research grounded in game theory, which has suggested that some alliance structures are inherently more likely than others to be associated with high opportunity to cheat, high behavioral uncertainty, and poor stability, longevity, and performance. The present study merged these theoretical insights with the logic of transaction cost economics in a general model of alliance structuring and tested it with data from 111 interfirm alliances. Findings generally supported the model and hypotheses, suggesting the need for a greater focus on game theoretic structural dimensions and institutional responses to perceived opportunism in the study of voluntary interfirm cooperation.
AB  - Maintaining robust cooperation in interfirm strategic alliances poses special problems. Such relationships have received growing attention in recent research grounded in game theory, which has suggested that some alliance structures are inherently more likely than others to be associated with high opportunity to cheat, high behavioral uncertainty, and poor stability, longevity, and performance. The present study merged these theoretical insights with the logic of transaction cost economics in a general model of alliance structuring and tested it with data from 111 interfirm alliances. Findings generally supported the model and hypotheses, suggesting the need for a greater focus on game theoretic structural dimensions and institutional responses to perceived opportunism in the study of voluntary interfirm cooperation.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256759
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256759
Y2  - 2026/04/24
